# ConvoDb

ConvoDb is a path-based, graph-capable database interface for building AI agents, agent memory systems, RAG pipelines, workflow engines, knowledge graphs, and other agentic systems.

It combines a few ideas that work especially well for modern AI applications:

- **Nodes** for storing entities, documents, tasks, tools, users, memories, and arbitrary structured data
- **Edges** for relationships, graph traversal, and permissions
- **Embeddings** for semantic search and retrieval
- **Filesystem-style paths** for intuitive organization and subtree-based access control
- **Portable adapters** so the same ConvoDb code can run in memory, in browsers, over HTTP, on the local filesystem, and on SQL backends

If you are building systems that need memory, retrieval, relationships, and permissions, ConvoDb gives you one consistent model that can span local development, browser apps, and production backends.

---

## Why ConvoDb

AI agents rarely fit cleanly into a single storage pattern.

Most agentic systems need some combination of:

- structured records
- hierarchical organization
- graph relationships
- semantic retrieval
- scoped permissions
- local and remote portability

ConvoDb is designed around those needs.

You can use it to power:

- agent memory
- long-running task graphs
- document stores
- tool registries
- user and tenant workspaces
- collaboration systems
- browser-based copilots
- local-first AI tools
- hybrid local/remote AI applications

---

## Core ideas

### Nodes

Nodes are the main records stored in ConvoDb.

A node has:

- a unique `path`
- a `type`
- arbitrary `data`
- optional metadata like `displayName`, `description`, `instructions`, and timestamps

Example:

```ts
const userNode={
    path:'/users/alex',
    type:'user',
    displayName:'Alex',
    data:{
        email:'alex@example.com',
        tier:'pro',
    },
};
```

Typical node types include:

- `user`
- `agent`
- `doc`
- `task`
- `workspace`
- `memory`
- `tool`
- `session`

---

### Edges

Edges connect nodes.

They are useful for:

- relationship graphs
- workflow dependency graphs
- membership and ownership
- tool access
- permission grants
- traversal queries

Examples:

- user belongs to workspace
- agent uses tool
- task depends on task
- message belongs to session
- user is granted access to a workspace subtree

---

### Embeddings

Embeddings attach semantic vector search capability to nodes.

This makes ConvoDb useful for:

- RAG pipelines
- semantic document search
- memory recall
- context retrieval
- similarity search

Embeddings point at a node path and usually reference a property such as `data.body` or `data.summary`.

---

## Filesystem-style paths

One of ConvoDb’s core design choices is that every node is identified by a normalized path that behaves like a filesystem path.

Examples:

- `/users/alex`
- `/users/alex/memory/profile`
- `/agents/researcher`
- `/workspaces/acme/docs/spec`
- `/orgs/acme/projects/project-1/tasks/task-42`

This makes your data feel like a structured namespace instead of a flat table.

### Why paths are powerful

Paths let you model application structure naturally:

- users under `/users/*`
- agents under `/agents/*`
- sessions under `/sessions/*`
- workspaces under `/workspaces/*`
- documents under `/docs/*`
- tenant data under `/tenants/*`

Example structure:

```txt
/users/alex
/users/alex/memory/preferences
/users/alex/memory/profile
/agents/researcher
/agents/researcher/tools/web-search
/workspaces/acme
/workspaces/acme/docs/spec
/workspaces/acme/tasks/task-1
```

### Path rules

ConvoDb paths are normalized and follow simple rules:

- paths start with `/`
- trailing slashes are removed except for `/`
- duplicate slashes are normalized
- paths are case-sensitive
- `.` and `..` are not allowed
- stored node paths cannot contain `*`
- wildcard query paths like `/users/*` are supported

---

## Filesystem-style permissions

The path model also makes permissions much easier to manage.

Instead of attaching access control to every single record independently, you can grant access at a meaningful root and let it apply to descendants.

For example, a grant to:

```txt
/workspaces/acme
```

can be used when checking access to:

```txt
/workspaces/acme/docs/spec
/workspaces/acme/tasks/task-1
/workspaces/acme/agents/researcher
```

This is similar to how filesystem permissions or mounted directory access are often reasoned about.

### Why this is useful

For agentic systems, subtree-based permissions are a very natural fit:

- grant a user access to a workspace
- grant an agent access to a memory subtree
- grant a tool runner execute access to a tool namespace
- grant a tenant-scoped service access to everything under a tenant root

This usually means:

- fewer permission records
- simpler access rules
- easier reasoning
- easier multi-tenant isolation

### Permission types

ConvoDb supports these permission bits:

- `read`
- `write`
- `execute`

And common combinations such as:

- `readWrite`
- `readExecute`
- `writeExecute`
- `all`

---

## Installation and imports

The `ConvoDb` interface and shared types are imported from:

```ts
import { ConvoDb, ConvoNodePermissionType } from '@convo-lang/convo-lang';
```

Adapters are imported from:

```ts
import { InMemoryConvoDb } from '@convo-lang/db';
```

---

## Quick start

### Create a database

```ts
import { InMemoryConvoDb } from '@convo-lang/db';

const db=new InMemoryConvoDb();
```

### Insert some nodes

```ts
await db.insertNodeAsync({
    path:'/users/alex',
    type:'user',
    displayName:'Alex',
    data:{
        role:'developer',
    },
});

await db.insertNodeAsync({
    path:'/airports/jfk',
    type:'airport',
    displayName:'JFK Airport',
    data:{
        city:'New York',
        code:'JFK',
    },
});

await db.insertNodeAsync({
    path:'/trips/alex-jfk',
    type:'trip',
    displayName:'Alex Trip to JFK',
    data:{
        status:'planning',
        destination:'/airports/jfk',
    },
});
```

### Query by path

```ts
const trips=await db.getNodesByPathAsync('/trips/*');

if(trips.success){
    console.log(trips.result.nodes);
}
```

---

## Use cases

ConvoDb is especially useful for developers building AI agents and other agentic systems.

### Agent memory

Use path namespaces to separate memory types:

```txt
/agents/researcher/memory/working/current-task
/agents/researcher/memory/episodic/2026-04-01
/agents/researcher/memory/semantic/product-facts
```

This makes it easy to:

- scope memory per agent
- clean up old memory by subtree
- apply permissions to whole memory areas
- support short-term and long-term memory patterns

---

### Multi-tenant AI workspaces

Model each tenant or workspace under its own root:

```txt
/tenants/acme
/tenants/acme/users/alex
/tenants/acme/docs/handbook
/tenants/acme/agents/support
```

This works well for:

- team copilots
- enterprise AI assistants
- customer-isolated workspaces
- tenant-level authorization

---

### Tool registries

Store tools as nodes:

```txt
/tools/web-search
/tools/calculator
/tools/sql-query
/tools/calendar
```

Then connect agents to the tools they are allowed to use with edges.

---

### Workflow and task graphs

Represent workflows and tasks with nodes and edges:

```txt
/workflows/onboarding
/workflows/onboarding/tasks/create-account
/workflows/onboarding/tasks/send-email
/workflows/onboarding/tasks/verify-access
```

Use edges for:

- depends on
- blocks
- assigned to
- completes
- triggers

---

### RAG and semantic retrieval

Store documents as nodes and add embeddings for semantic search:

```txt
/docs/product/overview
/docs/product/faq
/docs/product/pricing
```

This supports:

- retrieval pipelines
- semantic knowledge lookup
- document grounding
- memory recall for agents

---

### Conversation and session state

```txt
/sessions/session-001
/sessions/session-001/messages/msg-1
/sessions/session-001/messages/msg-2
/sessions/session-001/summary
```

Useful for:

- chat agents
- support copilots
- multi-step orchestration
- resumable agent sessions

---

## Basic CRUD

### Insert a node

```ts
await db.insertNodeAsync({
    path:'/agents/researcher',
    type:'agent',
    displayName:'Research Agent',
    data:{
        model:'example-model',
        goal:'Find and summarize useful information',
    },
});
```

### Update a node

Node updates are partial, but `data` is replaced as a whole when provided.

```ts
await db.updateNodeAsync({
    path:'/agents/researcher',
    displayName:'Research Agent v2',
    data:{
        model:'example-model',
        goal:'Find, rank, and summarize useful information',
    },
});
```

### Delete a node

Deleting a node also deletes:

- all connected edges
- all embeddings pointing to the node

```ts
await db.deleteNodeAsync('/agents/researcher');
```

---

## Querying nodes

ConvoDb queries are traversal-oriented.

A query contains one or more `steps`. Each step can:

- filter nodes by path
- filter by conditions
- filter by permissions
- filter by embeddings
- traverse connected edges to move to the next set of nodes

### Simple path query

```ts
const r=await db.queryNodesAsync({
    steps:[
        {
            path:'/users/*',
        },
    ],
});
```

### Query by nested data condition

```ts
const r=await db.queryNodesAsync({
    steps:[
        {
            path:'/users/*',
            condition:{
                target:'data.tier',
                op:'=',
                value:'pro',
            },
        },
    ],
});
```

### Query with sort order

```ts
const r=await db.queryNodesAsync({
    steps:[
        {
            path:'/docs/*',
        },
    ],
    orderBy:{
        prop:'path',
        direction:'asc',
    },
});
```

### Select only certain keys

```ts
const r=await db.queryNodesAsync({
    keys:['path','type','data'],
    steps:[
        {
            path:'/agents/*',
        },
    ],
});
```

### Pagination with `nextToken`

```ts
const firstPage=await db.queryNodesAsync({
    steps:[
        {
            path:'/docs/*',
        },
    ],
    limit:20,
});

if(firstPage.success && firstPage.result.nextToken){
    const secondPage=await db.queryNodesAsync({
        steps:[
            {
                path:'/docs/*',
            },
        ],
        limit:20,
        nextToken:firstPage.result.nextToken,
    });
}
```

### Stream results

Streaming is useful for large scans, ingestion, maintenance jobs, and indexing.

```ts
for await(const item of db.streamNodesAsync({
    steps:[
        {
            path:'/docs/*',
        },
    ],
})){
    if(item.type==='error'){
        console.error(item.error);
        break;
    }

    console.log(item.node.path);
}
```

---

## Conditions

Conditions can target top-level properties or nested values inside `data`.

### Simple condition

```ts
const r=await db.queryNodesAsync({
    steps:[
        {
            path:'/tasks/*',
            condition:{
                target:'data.status',
                op:'=',
                value:'open',
            },
        },
    ],
});
```

### Grouped conditions

```ts
const r=await db.queryNodesAsync({
    steps:[
        {
            path:'/tasks/*',
            condition:{
                groupOp:'and',
                conditions:[
                    {
                        target:'data.status',
                        op:'=',
                        value:'open',
                    },
                    {
                        target:'data.priority',
                        op:'>=',
                        value:3,
                    },
                ],
            },
        },
    ],
});
```

### Supported operator categories

Comparison operators:

- `=`
- `!=`
- `>`
- `<`
- `>=`
- `<=`

Array operators:

- `in`
- `all-in`
- `any-in`
- `contains`
- `contains-all`
- `contains-any`

Wildcard string operators:

- `like`
- `ilike`

---

## Working with edges

Edges make ConvoDb graph-aware.

You can query them directly or traverse them from node queries.

### Insert an edge

```ts
await db.insertEdgeAsync({
    type:'uses-tool',
    from:'/agents/researcher',
    to:'/tools/web-search',
    description:'Research agent can use the web search tool',
});
```

### Query edges directly

```ts
const edgeResult=await db.queryEdgesAsync({
    from:'/agents/researcher',
    type:'uses-tool',
});
```

### Traverse from one node to connected nodes

Find the tools used by an agent:

```ts
const r=await db.queryNodesAsync({
    steps:[
        {
            path:'/agents/researcher',
            edge:'uses-tool',
            edgeDirection:'forward',
        },
    ],
});
```

### Reverse traversal

Find agents that can use a tool:

```ts
const r=await db.queryNodesAsync({
    steps:[
        {
            path:'/tools/web-search',
            edge:'uses-tool',
            edgeDirection:'reverse',
        },
    ],
});
```

### Multi-step traversal

Move from a user to a workspace and then to nodes contained inside that workspace:

```ts
const r=await db.queryNodesAsync({
    steps:[
        {
            path:'/users/alex',
            edge:'member-of',
            edgeDirection:'forward',
        },
        {
            edge:'contains',
            edgeDirection:'forward',
        },
    ],
});
```

---

## Permissions

Permissions are represented using edges with the `grant` property.

This makes permission storage explicit, graph-aware, and easy to combine with path-based subtree semantics.

### Grant read/write access

```ts
import { ConvoNodePermissionType } from '@convo-lang/convo-lang';

await db.insertEdgeAsync({
    type:'grant',
    from:'/users/alex',
    to:'/workspaces/acme',
    grant:ConvoNodePermissionType.readWrite,
});
```

### Get effective permission

```ts
const permission=await db.getNodePermissionAsync(
    '/users/alex',
    '/workspaces/acme/docs/spec',
);

if(permission.success){
    console.log(permission.result);
}
```

### Check permission

```ts
const check=await db.checkNodePermissionAsync(
    '/users/alex',
    '/workspaces/acme/docs/spec',
    ConvoNodePermissionType.read,
);

if(check.success){
    console.log('allowed');
}
```

### Enforce permissions on reads

```ts
const docs=await db.queryNodesAsync({
    steps:[
        {
            path:'/workspaces/acme/docs/*',
        },
    ],
    permissionFrom:'/users/alex',
    permissionRequired:ConvoNodePermissionType.read,
});
```

### Enforce permissions on writes

```ts
await db.insertNodeAsync(
    {
        path:'/workspaces/acme/docs/new-doc',
        type:'doc',
        data:{
            title:'New Document',
        },
    },
    {
        permissionFrom:'/users/alex',
    },
);
```

### Why subtree permissions are so useful

Instead of granting access record-by-record, you can often grant at a boundary like:

- `/tenants/acme`
- `/workspaces/acme`
- `/agents/researcher/memory`
- `/tools`

That gives you a filesystem-style mental model that is much easier to manage as your data grows.

---

## Embeddings and semantic retrieval

Embeddings let you search nodes by meaning instead of only by exact fields.

### Insert a document node

```ts
await db.insertNodeAsync({
    path:'/docs/faq/refunds',
    type:'doc',
    data:{
        title:'Refund Policy',
        body:'Customers may request a refund within 30 days of purchase.',
    },
});
```

### Insert an embedding

```ts
await db.insertEmbeddingAsync({
    path:'/docs/faq/refunds',
    prop:'data.body',
    type:'text',
});
```

### Query embeddings directly

```ts
const embeddings=await db.queryEmbeddingsAsync({
    path:'/docs/faq/refunds',
});
```

### Semantic filtering in a node query

```ts
const r=await db.queryNodesAsync({
    steps:[
        {
            path:'/docs/*',
            embedding:{
                text:'How do refunds work?',
                type:'text',
            },
        },
    ],
});
```

### Embedding instructions

Embeddings may include `instructions` that describe how the source data should be transformed before vector generation.

This is useful when you want to:

- combine title and body
- summarize large objects before embedding
- embed selected fields only
- normalize content for better retrieval quality

---

## Command-based execution

ConvoDb also supports command objects. This is especially useful when you want to:

- proxy database operations over HTTP
- expose database actions as tool calls
- serialize operations between services
- build remote agent runtimes

### Execute a single command

```ts
const result=await db.executeCommandAsync({
    queryNodes:{
        query:{
            steps:[
                {
                    path:'/docs/*',
                },
            ],
        },
    },
});
```

### Execute multiple commands

```ts
const result=await db.executeCommandsAsync([
    {
        insertNode:{
            node:{
                path:'/agents/planner',
                type:'agent',
                data:{},
            },
        },
    },
    {
        queryNodes:{
            query:{
                steps:[
                    {
                        path:'/agents/*',
                    },
                ],
            },
        },
    },
]);
```

This command format works especially well with remote systems and tool-driven agent architectures.

---

## Adapters

A major benefit of ConvoDb is that your application can target the `ConvoDb` interface while different adapters handle storage.

That means your application logic can stay mostly the same while storage changes based on your environment, scale, or deployment model.

Adapters are imported from:

```ts
import {
    InMemoryConvoDb,
    LocalStorageConvoDb,
    HttpConvoDb,
} from '@convo-lang/db';
```

### Why adapters matter

Different agent systems need different storage strategies:

- in-memory for tests and prototypes
- browser storage for local-first apps
- HTTP proxying for remote services
- SQLite for embedded persistence
- Postgres for production backends
- layered setups for hybrid local/remote architectures

By coding against the `ConvoDb` interface, you can switch adapters without redesigning your data model.

---

## Current adapters

### `BaseConvoDb`

A base adapter that simplifies building custom adapters.

It provides shared logic for:

- query traversal
- permissions
- validation
- command execution
- embedding generation flow

Use it when implementing your own storage backend.

---

### `InMemoryConvoDb`

Stores data in memory.

Best for:

- tests
- demos
- prototypes
- temporary agent runs

---

### `BaseSqliteConvoDb`

An abstract SQLite adapter that allows you to build SQLite adapters by implementing a query function.

Best for:

- local persistent apps
- embedded tools
- desktop AI applications
- lightweight server storage

---

### `BunSqliteConvoDb`

A SQLite adapter using Bun’s SQLite implementation.

Best for:

- Bun-based local apps
- development environments
- compact persistent stores

---

### `BasePostgresConvoDb`

An abstract Postgres adapter that allows you to build Postgres adapters by implementing a query function.

Best for:

- production server systems
- shared backends
- scalable multi-user deployments

---

### `BunPostgresConvoDb`

A Postgres adapter using Bun’s Postgres implementation.

Best for:

- Bun server applications
- cloud APIs
- production AI backends

---

### `HttpConvoDb`

A proxy adapter that connects to a remote ConvoDb over HTTP.

Best for:

- browser clients
- remote workers
- service-based architectures
- centralized data layers

---

### `LocalStorageConvoDb`

Stores data in browser local storage.

Best for:

- small browser apps
- offline demos
- local prototypes
- single-user tools

---

### `IndexDbConvoDb`

Stores data in IndexedDB in the browser.

Best for:

- larger browser datasets
- offline-first AI apps
- local browser memory stores
- richer client-side persistence

---

### `FsConvoDb`

Stores data using the local filesystem.

Best for:

- CLIs
- local developer tools
- inspectable data storage
- local-first workflows

---

### `LayeredConvoDb`

A hybrid adapter that layers multiple adapters together and routes requests by path rules.

This is similar to how Unix filesystem mounts work.

Example uses:

- `/cache/*` in memory
- `/local/*` in IndexedDB
- `/shared/*` over HTTP
- `/archive/*` on disk

Best for:

- hybrid architectures
- local caching
- path-routed storage
- mixed local/remote systems

---

## Adapter examples

### In-memory prototype

```ts
import { InMemoryConvoDb } from '@convo-lang/db';

const db=new InMemoryConvoDb();
```

### Browser persistence

```ts
import { IndexDbConvoDb } from '@convo-lang/db';

const db=new IndexDbConvoDb();
```

### Remote API proxy

```ts
import { HttpConvoDb } from '@convo-lang/db';

const db=new HttpConvoDb({
    baseUrl:'https://api.example.com/convo-db',
});
```

### Layered hybrid storage

```ts
import {
    InMemoryConvoDb,
    HttpConvoDb,
    LayeredConvoDb,
} from '@convo-lang/db';

const cacheDb=new InMemoryConvoDb();
const remoteDb=new HttpConvoDb({
    baseUrl:'https://api.example.com/convo-db',
});

const db=new LayeredConvoDb({
    layers:[
        {
            path:'/agents/*',
            db:cacheDb,
        },
        {
            path:'/shared/*',
            db:remoteDb,
        },
    ],
});
```

---

## Recommended modeling patterns

### Use paths as stable namespaces

Good:

```txt
/users/alex
/users/alex/preferences
/users/alex/memory/profile
```

Less useful:

```txt
/item-1
/item-2
/item-3
```

Hierarchical paths make organization, querying, and permissions much simpler.

---

### Keep `type` meaningful

Good examples:

- `user`
- `agent`
- `doc`
- `task`
- `workspace`
- `memory`
- `tool`

---

### Put domain content in `data`

Use the node’s top-level properties for metadata and use `data` for your application-specific content.

---

### Use paths for hierarchy and edges for relationships

Paths tell you where something lives.

Edges tell you how things relate.

You usually want both.

Example:

- a task lives under `/workflows/onboarding/tasks/create-account`
- an edge says it `depends-on` another task

---

### Grant permissions high in the tree when possible

Prefer granting access at a root like:

```txt
/workspaces/acme
```

instead of one node at a time like:

```txt
/workspaces/acme/docs/doc-1
/workspaces/acme/docs/doc-2
/workspaces/acme/docs/doc-3
```

This keeps authorization simpler and more maintainable.

---

## End-to-end example

```ts
import { InMemoryConvoDb } from '@convo-lang/db';
import { ConvoNodePermissionType } from '@convo-lang/convo-lang';

const db=new InMemoryConvoDb();

await db.insertNodeAsync({
    path:'/users/alex',
    type:'user',
    data:{
        role:'admin',
    },
});

await db.insertNodeAsync({
    path:'/workspaces/acme',
    type:'workspace',
    data:{
        name:'Acme Workspace',
    },
});

await db.insertNodeAsync({
    path:'/workspaces/acme/docs/spec',
    type:'doc',
    data:{
        title:'System Spec',
        body:'This workspace contains product requirements and architecture notes.',
    },
});

await db.insertEdgeAsync({
    type:'grant',
    from:'/users/alex',
    to:'/workspaces/acme',
    grant:ConvoNodePermissionType.readWrite,
});

const docs=await db.queryNodesAsync({
    steps:[
        {
            path:'/workspaces/acme/docs/*',
        },
    ],
    permissionFrom:'/users/alex',
    permissionRequired:ConvoNodePermissionType.read,
});

if(docs.success){
    console.log(docs.result.nodes);
}
```

---

## Summary

ConvoDb is a strong fit for developers building:

- AI agents
- memory systems
- RAG workflows
- graph-shaped knowledge systems
- multi-tenant AI applications
- browser-based copilots
- local-first AI tools
- workflow and orchestration engines

Its key strengths are:

- **path-based organization**
- **filesystem-style permission modeling**
- **graph traversal with edges**
- **semantic retrieval with embeddings**
- **adapter-based portability across environments**

If your system needs structure, retrieval, relationships, and access control, ConvoDb provides a clean and portable foundation.

